  "opinion": "As a woman who’s been working in Chicago’s construction trades for over twenty years, I’ve seen firsthand how the gender gap in science isn’t just a statistic—it’s a lived reality for many of us. My own journey started in a world where science was rarely associated with hands-on work like carpentry, yet I’ve always been fascinated by how things work. Growing up in a household where my father earned a vocational diploma and my mother had an upper secondary education, I learned early that opportunities weren’t always equal. Today, when I talk to my children about science, I emphasize that it’s not just for those who wear lab coats—it’s in the way we build, fix, and understand the world. The gender gap in science isn’t just about who gets hired; it’s about who feels they belong. For many women, especially those from working-class backgrounds, science can feel like a distant dream because the systems that shape our education and careers don’t always reflect our experiences. We should address this gap by creating spaces where everyone feels seen and valued—not just in labs, but in the shops, the classrooms, and the community centers where science is practiced. It starts with listening to those who’ve been left out, like the women in my neighborhood who work in trades but don’t have access to STEM resources. My own experience as a carpenter has taught me that science isn’t confined to textbooks—it’s in the measurements, the angles, the problem-solving that keeps our communities running. So yes, we must address this gap, but we have to do it in ways that honor the real-world contexts where people live and work, not just in abstract discussions about 'diversity.'",
